reasoning:
First off, GOOG sits well outside my Circle of Competence. I’ve spent my life studying simple, predictable businesses—retailing candy, insurance, railroads and consumer staples—not the intricacies of search algorithms and ad auctions. When you can’t grasp a business model end-to-end, you’ve just added risk, plain and simple.

On the moat side, Alphabet certainly enjoys a strong position in search and online advertising, but network effects and lumpy regulatory risks temper its durability. It isn’t like Coca-Cola’s brand, which consumers will sip whether the economy is hot or cold. Ad spending can shift rapidly, and I worry about possible antitrust actions and an ever-evolving competitive landscape.

Management at Google has shown technical prowess, yet enormous R&D outlays and speculative bets on moonshots aren’t exactly the hallmark of capital discipline I prize. A conservative balance sheet is nice, but I need consistent, understandable earnings and clear capital allocation—a table of numbers I simply don’t have here.

With no reliable intrinsic value estimate, no margin of safety and no evidence that I can project future free cash flows with any comfort, I can’t justify a purchase. For me, a wonderful business at a fair price beats a fair business at a wonderful price. GOOG, under these circumstances, feels like the latter.

Compared to opportunities I’ve found in consumer staples or banks—where I can state with confidence what the business will earn 10 years from now—GOOG is a pass. I’d rather hold my cash than gamble on complexity I don’t understand.
